-- Sub-Sahara Africa Stocks: Benso, African Petroleum and ASL
-- B y   V i n c e n t   N w a n m a   a n d   K a m l e s h   B h u c k o r y
-- 2010-12-09T16:27:14Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-12-09/sub-sahara-africa-stocks-african-petroleum-asl-of-mauritius.html
Mauritius’s  SEMDEX Index  dropped for
the first day in eight, declining 0.4 percent to 1,929.41 at the
1:30 p.m. close in Port Louis.  Namibia’s  FTSE/Namibia Overall Index  fell 0.9 percent to
836.17 by the 5 p.m. close in Windhoek and the  Nigerian Stock
Exchange All-Share Index  declined 0.3 percent to 24,601.28 at
the 2:30 p.m. close in Lagos, the commercial capital.  The  Ghana Stock Exchange All-Share Index  rose less than
0.1. percent to 7,127.81 at the 1 p.m. in Accra. Kenya’s  All-
Share Index  rose for a second day, increasing 0.3 percent to
close at 78.91 at 3 p.m. in Nairobi.  The following shares rose or fell in sub-Saharan Africa,
excluding South Africa. Stock symbols are in parentheses.  African Petroleum Plc  (APET NL), a Nigerian fuel retailer,
rallied for a second day, climbing 1 naira, or 5 percent, to 21
naira. in Lagos.  The company reported third-quarter profit of 899.5 million
naira ($5.9 million) compared with a loss of 5.56 billion naira
a year earlier, according to a statement e-mailed yesterday by
the Nigerian Stock Exchange.  Automated Systems Ltd.  (ASL MP) dropped 7 Mauritian rupees,
or 5.8 percent, to 113 rupees, the lowest in three months, in
Port Louis.  The betting-systems operator fell as investors speculated
that proposed new taxes on gambling may reduce its profit next
year, Vikash Tulsidas, manager of Port-Louis based Axys
Stockbroking Ltd., said in an e-mailed response to questions.  Benso Oil Palm Plantation Ltd.  (BOPP GN), the oil-palm
plantation operator, rose the most since May as favorable
weather boosted crop yield expectations. Benso rose 5 pesewas,
or 7.7 percent, to 70 pesewas.  Cal Bank Ltd.  {CAL GN), a Ghanaian lender, rose 1 pesewa,
or 3.5 percent, to 30 pesewas. The company may hold a rights
offer to raise money to participate in funding the country’s
nascent oil industry, Emmanuel Tsingbey, a stock broker with
Renaissance Capital, said in an interview.  To contact the reporters on this story:
